## Commands

```bash
cd backend && pytest            # Backend contract + integration tests (FakeGCPProvider — no cloud calls)
cd frontend && pytest           # Frontend integration tests
cd backend && ruff check .      # Lint backend
cd frontend && ruff check .     # Lint frontend
cd backend && uvicorn src.main:app --reload   # Run backend dev server
cd frontend && streamlit run src/app.py       # Run frontend dev server

# Opt-in manifest validation against a real Kubernetes API server using server-side dry-run.
# Requires a scratch kubeconfig; NEVER creates real resources (dry_run=["All"]).
LLMOPS_K8S_DRYRUN_KUBECONFIG=~/.kube/scratch-config \
  cd backend && pytest tests/dryrun
```

## Testing Policy (mandatory)

- **Tests MUST NOT call real cloud services.** The default `pytest` run touches zero GCP APIs, creates zero projects, launches zero clusters, incurs zero cost.
- The GCP boundary is crossed only through the `GCPProvider` protocol. Tests inject `FakeGCPProvider`; production injects `RealGCPProvider`. No test may import `RealGCPProvider`.
- Where a real-fidelity check is desired, prefer **dry-run** over live side effects:
  - **Kubernetes manifests**: validate with the Python `kubernetes` client using `dry_run=["All"]` (server-side dry-run). Gated on `LLMOPS_K8S_DRYRUN_KUBECONFIG` — suite is skipped when unset. Still does not touch GCP.
  - **GCP Resource Manager / Billing / GKE cluster create**: these APIs expose no dry-run flag. Do NOT invent a "live smoke" suite that calls them; rely on the fake + manual end-to-end verification before release.
- CI runs `pytest` with no cloud env vars set. Any test that requires network access to a cloud endpoint is either (a) gated behind an env var and skipped by default, or (b) rejected in review.

